                        Bubble Sort is a simple sorting algorithm known for its ease of
                        implementation and low space complexity. It compares adjacent elements in a list and swaps
                        them if they are in the wrong order, gradually moving the larger elements towards the end of the list.
                        While it is adaptive to some extent, performing well on partially sorted lists,
                        Bubble Sort's main drawback is its inefficiency for large datasets,
                        with a time complexity of O(n^2) in the worst case. Despite its simplicity,
                        it may not be the optimal choice for large-scale sorting tasks,
                        and more efficient algorithms like Merge Sort or Quick Sort are often preferred in such scenarios.
